Fraud detection in mobile money systems presents significant challenges due to the high volume of transactions, class imbalance, and evolving fraud patterns. This study presents a comprehensive evaluation of Isolation Forest, an unsupervised anomaly detection algorithm, for fraud detection in mobile money and digital wallet systems. Unlike supervised approaches that require labeled fraud data, Isolation Forest operates by isolating anomalies through recursive data partitioning, making it particularly suitable for scenarios where fraud labels are scarce or unreliable. We evaluate the method on a credit card fraud detection dataset comprising approximately 284,807 transactions with a fraud rate of 0.172\%, demonstrating its effectiveness through comprehensive metrics including precision, recall, F1-score, PR-AUC, and ROC-AUC. Our experimental results show that Isolation Forest achieves competitive performance compared to supervised models such as Logistic Regression, Random Forest, and XGBoost, while offering advantages in scalability and adaptability to unlabeled data scenarios. The study also examines the practical implications for U.S. digital wallets and underbanked communities, addressing regulatory compliance, operational scalability, and user-centered design considerations. The findings demonstrate that Isolation Forest provides a viable solution for real-time fraud detection in large-scale financial systems, with particular relevance for protecting vulnerable populations in digital financial ecosystems.}
