1.0 Introduction}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
1.1 Background on Mobile Money Systems}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
More specifically, mobile money has resulted in financial inclusion, especially to the segment of the African population that lacked access to traditional banking (Konte & Tetteh, 2023). Some of the services that have empowered individuals to save, transfer and receive money safely using handheld devices include mobile wallets, agent networks and peer-to-peer transfers. The system has broadened the opportunities in the economy, reduced the amount of cash in use, and increased the availability of remittances and government transfers. Similarly, the underbanked demographics are beginning to adopt the use of U.S digital wallets, peer-to-peer payment apps, and prepaid cards, which are convenient and fast (Matenga, 2025a). Such changes indicate that more fraud detection systems based on smartness will be required to secure the users and financial systems.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
1.2 Problem Statement}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
One of the significant threats is fraud in digital financial systems, particularly for low-income users or those with weak financial backgrounds. Transaction irregularities, account theft, and unauthorised transfers can cost substantial sums of money and cause mistrust in digital services (Enyiorji & Deloitte, 2023). Manual inspection and rule-based notification are also not always capable of detecting unnoticeable or new fraudulent activity on a real-time basis, as opposed to traditional monitoring tools. Automated, scalable, and adaptive solutions to these challenges are realized by artificial intelligence and machine learning solutions, especially anomaly detection algorithms. With the isolation of abnormal transaction habits, such models can take the initiative to prevent financial losses and cushion the underbanked (Donkor, 2025).}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
1.3 Objectives of the Study}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
The paper will re-implement and experiment with the Isolation Forest model to detect fraud in the mobile banking system. It will look at how the algorithm is able to detect anomalous transactions with high accuracy and low false-positive rates. The success of the Isolation Forest will be checked against other machine learning models, such as tree-based models or neural network models. The study will also examine the viability of such systems in the U.S. digital wallets with reference to compliance with regulatory provisions, operational limitations, and security of the user. Results of the study will be used in further measures of implementing AI-based fraud detection in various financial ecosystems.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\qc\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
2.0 Data and Context}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
2.1 Mobile Money Transaction Datasets }
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Mobile money transaction datasets were developed using the real-life datasets of mobile money transfer (Konte & Tetteh, 2023). The study relies on anonymous and simulated data on transactions that are related to the real-world use of mobile money. The data sets contain the major attributes, such as amounts of transactions, time, frequency, device identifiers, and geolocation data. The features will give a detailed picture of user behavior and will help to describe anomalous activity. Preprocessing of data makes sure that the missing values, inconsistent formats, and outliers are treated accordingly so that the quality of the data is not compromised (Enyiorji & Deloitte, 2023). These datasets enable strong model training and evaluation, which serves to guarantee that the Isolation Forest can adequately separate legitimate and fraudulent transactions in realistic conditions because they reflect different transaction scenarios.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
2.2 Comparative Ecosystem Analysis}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
According to Regragui. (2022), African mobile money systems are not in the same category as the U.S. digital wallets and use of prepaid cards in some important aspects. The African systems tend to use agent networks, cash-in points, cash-out points, and mobile phone penetration, whereas the U.S. systems are directly linked with bank accounts, cards, and app-based peer-to-peer networks (Srinivasan, 2021). The knowledge of these differences is critical to adjusting the model because transaction patterns, fraud vectors, and user behavior differ in different regions. The comparative analysis will enable the study to find out the characteristics of relevance, future challenges, and lessons to be learned by existing systems. Such a cross-context analysis can guide not only algorithm design but also practical implementation instruments to underbanked U.S. populations.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
2.3 Feature Engineering and Data Preprocessing}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Frauds are difficult to detect without appropriate preprocessing and feature engineering. The gaps or missing data should be dealt with by the use of imputation and normalization. Categorical variables, use of which is a transaction type or a device ID, are coded accordingly to machine learning models. The scaling of features will bring about comparability of the features that are numeric, and feature selection will be used to select the most predictive features in order to enhance the performance of a model. Moreover, the derived features, such as the frequency of transactions, average amounts, and location consistency, can be added to improve the abilities of anomaly detection. Those measures minimize noise, enhance interpretability, and make the most of the Isolation Forest to detect fraudulent behavior correctly in both the African and U.S. settings.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\qc\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
3.0 Methodology}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
3.1 Isolation Forest Model Architecture }
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Isolation Forest separates anomalies through recursive division of data, whereby numerous decision trees are formed. Enyiorji (2025) states that anomalies have less path length, as they are very different compared to the larger number of transactions. This method does not make any assumptions regarding data distribution, and this is why it is very flexible when dealing with heterogeneous mobile money data. Its processing ability with large data is one of its strengths, as it can process millions of transactions quickly. Isolation Forest has another advantage of scalability, which is appropriate for expanding digital wallet ecosystems. In contrast to distance-based techniques, it can deal with large-scale data without growing computation needs exponentially (Regragui, 2022). One of the limitations is interpretability because the tree paths of individual trees provide little information on why transactions are flagged (Xu et al., 2023). This becomes a problem for transparency in the operation, especially in financial cooperation and compliance contexts. Nevertheless, it is possible to improve the use of Isolation Forest products with a visualization dashboard. Practically, the feature choice (e.g., transaction amount, frequency, and device identifiers) is sensitive and therefore improves detection accuracy. Such critical tuning makes the system adaptive to changing user behaviors in different populations. Nevertheless, it may produce false positives when there are irrelevant or noisy features (Donkor, 2025). Tuning of parameters such as the number of trees and the number of maximum samples is necessary in order to achieve a balance between the accuracy of detection and the cost of computation.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
3.3 Training Strategy}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
The best training of models requires the division of the dataset into training and testing parts. As Zainab et al. (2025) indicate, the reliability of the model implementation can be improved with the help of k-fold cross-validation, which verifies the model's performance on various sets of data. For Isolation Forest, training is performed on normal (non-fraudulent) transactions only, as it is an unsupervised anomaly detection method. This approach eliminates the need for labeled fraud data during training, making it particularly suitable for scenarios where fraud labels are scarce or unreliable. The model learns the patterns of normal transactions and identifies deviations as potential fraud.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
3.4 Validation Strategy}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Validation is used to ensure that the model performs well on previously unknown data. For Isolation Forest, validation involves generating anomaly scores for transactions in the validation set and converting these scores to fraud probabilities. Threshold optimization is performed on the validation set to determine the optimal decision threshold that maximizes F1-score or balances precision and recall according to business requirements. The strong performance evaluation and flexibility to new trends in transactions are strengths (Srinivasan, 2021). Computational intensity is a weakness, as is the need to carefully separate training and test data to prevent leakage. The performance of the model over time must be monitored to ensure that detection accuracy is maintained as fraud patterns evolve. The use of real-time feedback from operational deployment can enhance the effectiveness of the system in detecting emerging anomalies and reducing false positives.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
3.4 Evaluation Metrics}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
The assessment of models requires various measures to define the efficiency of detection. Precision, recall, F1-score, PR-AUC, ROC-AUC, and confusion matrices are used (Matenga, 2025a). Precision focuses on the percentage of successful identification of anomalies, whereas recall focuses on the possibility of identifying all frauds. These are balanced by the F1 score, which provides a single measure of performance. ROC-AUC compares tradeoffs between false positives and true positives, which are important when false alarms are costly in terms of operational costs. PR-AUC is particularly valuable for imbalanced datasets, as it focuses on the precision-recall tradeoff. Confusion matrices provide granular insight into model performance. According to Manousi et al. (2023), the benefits of multiple metrics are that they can provide complementary evaluation of performance, and the weakness is that they are sensitive to class imbalance and therefore can conceal poor anomaly prediction despite strong overall performance. Most importantly, there is no single metric that can give a holistic picture of performance. The integration of accuracy, recall, and ROC-AUC is useful to indicate possible flaws, e.g., over-flagging lawful transactions or overlooking minor anomalies (Kanumuri, 2025). High recall and low precision indicate that there are too many false positives, whereas high precision and low recall indicate that anomalies are missed. False positives and false negatives can be precisely analyzed through confusion matrices, and actionable information can be utilized in refining the model. The Isolation Forest can trade off operational efficiency and detection rate by adjusting parameters and testing their performance. Such a multi-metric approach builds trust in real-world usage and uncovers constraints.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
3.7 Comparison to Other Methods}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Other techniques are used to measure the Isolation Forest performance. Enyiorji (2025) states that Local Outlier Factor (LOF) detects conflicts by calculating deviations of local density. It is sensitive to local patterns as its strength, which is not computationally efficient with large-scale datasets. Autoencoders are able to rebuild input data, indicating anomalies via reconstruction error, and are able to model nonlinear, complex patterns. They have strong detection of subtle anomalies. The challenges that are associated with weaknesses are complicated training and reliance on huge datasets (Manousi et al., 2023). These approaches have tradeoffs to interpretability, computational efficiency, and scalability in mobile money fraud detection, as compared to Isolation Forest.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
The GB Trees offer both supervised learning and high interpretability, which is appropriate when there is labeled fraud data. Among the strengths are predictive accuracy and feature importance insights. Risks of overfitting and heavy dependency on large volumes of labeled data are weaknesses, which are likely to be constrained by the mobile money systems of reality. Each approach is best in a specific scenario: The Isolation Forest is superior in scaling and unlabeled data, whereas autoencoders and boosted trees are superior in complex patterns or supervised situations (Chabchoub et al., 2022). Operational choice is based on the constraints of the system, the availability of data, and regulatory conditions, focusing on the hybrid approaches to the best fraud detection.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
3.8 Critical Considerations for Implementation}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Implementation requires feature engineering, parameter tuning, and operational monitoring. Hassan et al. (2022) indicate that characteristics such as transaction frequency, transaction volumes, and geolocation enhance anomaly detection. Its strengths are that it is adaptable and scalable, and its weaknesses are lack of interpretability and the potential for false positives. Continuous retraining is necessary to learn new fraud trends. The inclusion of model outputs in dashboards with alert levels ensures actionable insights (Kanumuri, 2025). The methodology should balance detection rate, user impact, and regulatory compliance. Importantly, early detection of model drift and feedback mechanisms are robust to changes. Finally, the integration of Isolation Forest with complementary techniques provides a viable solution to mobile money fraud detection that is scalable.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\qc\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
4.0 Results and Experimental Validation}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
4.1 Dataset Description}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
We evaluated Isolation Forest on the Credit Card Fraud Detection dataset from Kaggle (Machine Learning Group - ULB, 2016), which contains 284,807 transactions. The dataset includes 28 anonymized features (V1-V28) derived from PCA transformations, along with Time and Amount features. The class distribution is highly imbalanced, with fraud representing 0.173\% of transactions (492 fraudulent transactions out of 284,807 total, with 284,315 legitimate transactions). The data was split into training (170,884 transactions, 60\%), validation (56,961 transactions, 20\%), and test (56,962 transactions, 20\%) sets using stratified sampling to maintain class distribution across splits. Feature engineering was applied to create time-based features (hour of day, day of dataset, time of day), amount transformations (log, square root, standardization, categorization), and interaction terms between Amount and key principal components. These engineered features enhance the model's ability to detect anomalous patterns in transaction behavior. Table 1 summarizes the dataset statistics.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
4.2 Experimental Setup}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Isolation Forest was implemented using the isotree package in R. The model was configured with ntrees=100, sample_size=256, and max_depth=ceiling(log2(256)). Training was performed unsupervised on normal (non-fraudulent) transactions only from the training set (170,884 transactions, excluding the 492 fraud cases). Anomaly scores were generated for both validation (56,961 transactions) and test (56,962 transactions) sets, then converted to fraud probabilities using the formula: prob_fraud = 1 - normalized_score. Threshold optimization was performed on the validation set by evaluating multiple thresholds (0.3, 0.4, 0.5, 0.6, 0.7) and selecting the threshold that maximized F1-score. The optimal threshold of 0.7 was then applied to the test set for final evaluation. For comparison, supervised models (Logistic Regression, Random Forest, XGBoost, Ensemble) were evaluated using the same train/validation/test split, with class weights applied to address imbalance. All models were evaluated using comprehensive metrics: Precision, Recall, F1-Score, MCC, PR-AUC, and ROC-AUC.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
