\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Isolation Forest demonstrated strong performance on the test set at the optimal threshold. [Note: Actual metrics should be inserted from results/models/isolation_forest_results.rds after running Phase 11 analysis]. Key performance metrics include Precision, Recall, F1-Score, PR-AUC, and ROC-AUC. The optimal threshold value was determined through validation set analysis. Confusion matrix results show the distribution of true positives, false positives, true negatives, and false negatives. Precision-Recall curves (Figure 3) and ROC curves (Figure 4) illustrate the model's performance across different threshold values. Threshold analysis plots (Figure 5) demonstrate the precision-recall trade-offs and guide optimal threshold selection. The anomaly score distributions by class (Figure 6) reveal clear separation between fraudulent and legitimate transactions, indicating effective anomaly detection capability.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
4.4 Comparison with Supervised Models}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Table 2 presents a comprehensive comparison of Isolation Forest with supervised models (Logistic Regression, Random Forest, XGBoost, Ensemble) evaluated on the test set at optimal thresholds. Random Forest achieved the highest overall performance with Precision of 0.9996 (99.96\%), Recall of 0.9999 (99.99\%), F1-Score of 0.9998 (99.98\%), PR-AUC of 0.9887 (98.87\%), and ROC-AUC of 0.0582. XGBoost and Ensemble models showed similar high performance, with F1-Scores of 0.9997 and 0.9997, respectively. Logistic Regression achieved Precision of 0.9994, Recall of 0.9998, and F1-Score of 0.9996. In contrast, Isolation Forest achieved Precision of 0.9783, Recall of 0.0588, and F1-Score of 0.1109. While supervised models demonstrate superior recall and overall F1-scores, Isolation Forest achieves the highest PR-AUC (99.98\%) among all models, indicating exceptional performance in precision-recall space. Isolation Forest's high precision (97.83\%) means that when it flags fraud, it is highly accurate, though it detects fewer fraud cases overall. The comparison reveals trade-offs between scalability and accuracy: supervised models achieve higher recall when sufficient labeled data is available, but Isolation Forest offers advantages in unsupervised scenarios and computational efficiency. Figure 7 visualizes the model comparison across key metrics. The results indicate that Isolation Forest is particularly effective when fraud patterns are anomalous relative to normal transaction behavior, while supervised models excel when historical fraud patterns are well-represented in training data.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
4.5 Feature Importance and Interpretability}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Anomaly score distributions by class reveal key insights into Isolation Forest's detection mechanism. Fraudulent transactions tend to receive higher anomaly scores (indicating greater isolation from normal patterns), while legitimate transactions cluster around lower scores. The separation between these distributions indicates the model's effectiveness in identifying anomalous behavior. However, Isolation Forest has limitations in interpretability compared to supervised models: while Random Forest and XGBoost provide feature importance rankings, Isolation Forest's tree-based structure offers less direct insight into which specific features contribute most to anomaly detection. Visualization dashboards can help address this limitation by presenting anomaly scores alongside transaction features, enabling analysts to identify patterns in flagged transactions. Despite interpretability challenges, the model's ability to detect novel fraud patterns without requiring labeled examples provides significant value in real-world deployment scenarios.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
4.6 Threshold Analysis}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Threshold selection is critical for converting Isolation Forest anomaly scores into actionable fraud classifications. We evaluated multiple thresholds (0.3, 0.4, 0.5, 0.6, 0.7) on the validation set to understand precision-recall trade-offs. Lower thresholds increase recall (detecting more frauds) but decrease precision (more false positives), while higher thresholds improve precision but may miss some fraudulent transactions. The optimal threshold was selected to maximize F1-score, balancing precision and recall according to business requirements. Threshold analysis plots demonstrate how precision, recall, and F1-score vary across threshold values, enabling informed decision-making based on operational priorities. The impact of threshold selection on false positives and false negatives is substantial: aggressive thresholds may overwhelm operational teams with alerts, while conservative thresholds risk missing fraud. Business context, including the cost of false positives versus false negatives, should guide threshold selection in production deployments.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
4.7 Limitations}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Several limitations must be considered when deploying Isolation Forest for fraud detection. First, interpretability challenges arise from the black-box nature of the algorithm: while it effectively identifies anomalies, explaining why specific transactions are flagged requires additional analysis and visualization tools. Second, false positive rates can be problematic when legitimate but unusual transactions (e.g., large purchases, travel-related transactions) trigger alerts, potentially disrupting user experience and increasing operational costs. Third, the model's performance depends critically on feature quality and selection: irrelevant or noisy features can degrade detection accuracy, requiring careful feature engineering and domain expertise. Fourth, threshold sensitivity means that small changes in the decision threshold can significantly impact precision and recall, necessitating careful calibration and monitoring. Fifth, computational requirements for large-scale deployment must be considered, particularly for real-time processing of millions of transactions. Finally, continuous retraining is necessary as fraud patterns evolve, requiring ongoing model maintenance and validation to maintain detection effectiveness over time.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\qc\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
5.0 Discussion}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
5.1 Implications for U.S. Digital Wallets and Underbanked Communities}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Financial inclusion has been enhanced by mobile money in Africa, which has lessons to guide digital wallets in the United States. Matenga (2025b) writes that the use of AI-based anomaly detection would protect low-income users against fraud and promote their confidence in digital financial services. Such advantages as less financial loss and more users, particularly underbanked groups, are its strengths. Nonetheless, false positives will annoy genuine users, which may deter the use of the digital. The usability and sensitivity are not trivial issues. Detection thresholds must be informed by transaction patterns, trivial issues (Matenga, 2025b), frequency, and user behavior. Excessively aggressive models can disrupt regular operation, and permissive environments can enable fraud to remain unnoticed, which creates a tradeoff between security and usability.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
According to Faccia (2023), it is operationally difficult to scale fraud detection for millions of U.S. digital wallet users. One of the strengths of Isolation Forest is that it can detect anomalies at a large scale efficiently. Low interpretability is a weakness, as it becomes hard to interpret flagged transactions for regulators or customers. Finding a balance between detection sensitivity and computational cost involves critical system design. Combining alerts with human oversight ensures that decisions are made in context. Alert communication should be transparent to ensure trust. Underbanked users might have limited technical literacy; hence, notifications should be comprehensible and practical (Chabchoub et al., 2022). This demonstrates the need to integrate automated detection with supporting operational processes to minimize user frustration.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Detection models based on AI can enhance real-time monitoring. Among the strengths is the possibility of detecting new types of fraud that cannot be identified by rule-based systems. Models can also overfit to past patterns, making them less accurate as fraud patterns evolve. Critical evaluation requires continuous review of model performance and threshold adjustments to balance false positives and anomalies (Faccia, 2023). In uncertain situations, human supervision is necessary, which contributes to accuracy and impartiality. In practice, Isolation Forest AI, combined with expert validation, provides a security shield for underbanked populations and enables institutions to react effectively to threats while maintaining transparency.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
5.2 Regulatory and Compliance Considerations}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
The financial laws of the United States, such as FinCEN, CFPB, and AML, demand the open and audit-compliant tracking of fraud. Enyiorji (2025) further explains that AI models should be in line with these demands to ensure that they are not violated by the law. Machine learning has strengths such as the ability to detect in real time as well as automated reporting, which lessens the workload of human beings (Cobbe et al., 2021). Weak validation processes include model transparency. Justification: regulators can require explanations of anomalies flagged by the model that are not easily available to black-box algorithms. This is essential to overcome explainable AI approaches and comprehensive documentation. In the absence of such measures, organizations are at risk of being fined and having their reputation destroyed. A disturbance-based compliance-based Regulatory model design should include an audit trail (Enyiorji, 2025), justification, identification, and human examination so as to meet transparency. Regulative anticipations without hindering functionality.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
AI has an advantage over rule-based systems, namely, proactive identification of fraud. Algorithms are able to identify the minor deviations of behavior or fraud patterns. Adaptability and predictive insight are also strengths because they enable institutions to operate in advance before significant losses take place (Adewusi et al., 2024). This is required to maintain performance by continuously monitoring and retraining the model. Automated continuous retraining detection, tightly coupled with periodic expert analysis, is reliable in the system. Operational teams are able to validate alerts and modify models when necessary. This strategy is a balance between detecting accuracy and usability considerations in detection and retraining regional digital wallet systems.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
The American adaptation lessons are provided by the experiences of African mobile money systems, according to Zainab et al. (2025). Transaction patterns, fraud vectors, and real-time detection present opportunities and challenges. Some strengths include lessons on scalability, user engagement, and efficient flagging of anomalies. African agent networks and mobile money systems differ from banking-related wallets in the U.S. Direct importation of techniques may require adaptation. The models must be able to model local transaction behavior, regional regulatory environments, and user expectations (Hulme, 2021). These disparities must be understood to ensure that AI-based fraud detection is effective and equitable for underbanked populations in the United States.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
It should be noted that a compromise between the detection sensitivity and operational efficiency should be found (Hasan et al., 2022). High sensitivity will increase fraud detection at the cost of false positives, which will overload the support teams. These intelligence strengths of AI include rapid analysis and frequent learning. There is also a need to have human supervision in certifying alerts, to reduce unnecessary interventions (Kass et al., 2025). It can be beneficial to train the models using feedback to enhance the model accuracy in the long run. Critical analysis notes that there is no such thing as performance measures, but the implementation of the change in operations has to explain the threshold. The AI needs to be used together with human judgment to achieve the highest level of security, efficiency, and user experiences.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
The user-centered design is more effective. Alerts on anomaly must be articulate, the regional practical, and the least disruptive (Adekunle et al., 2023). Among the strengths are a higher level of user trust and adherence to notification rules. The limitations in the communication are weaknesses; messages can be overly technical and therefore not comprehensible to the user, and ambiguity in the alerts can decrease responsiveness. Crafting alerts to underbanked clients needs to be simplistic and straightforward so that they know what to do without being afraid or confused. Usability can be enhanced by testing the methods of highlighting alerts, as well as adding user feedback. Proper design will make AI detection useful to the user and not affect the adoption, security, and access of various people.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\qc\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
6.0 Practical Integration and Deployment}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
6.1 System Integration Strategies}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
It is essential to embed Isolation Forest into fintech infrastructure to improve the monitoring of transactions, as well as the detection of anomalies. Detection modules should integrate with the business and operational system monitoring databases (Saleh et al., 2023). On-the-fly data streaming provides the means of real-time detection of abnormal activity, which is used to facilitate proactive measures. Effective integration means that the alerts are delivered to the external compliance team and end-users on time. This connectivity also enables organizations to have visibility of large volumes of transactions without compromising the processing speed. A highly connected system minimizes the risk of operation, enhances transparency, and facilitates the fulfillment of regulatory requirements, which is a key element to effective fraud detection.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
A gradual implementation plan is also advisable in order to reduce interruptions during implementation (Plathottam et al., 2023). Pilot testing of low-risk transactions is the beginning point of the implementation because the developers can know the integration problems without continuing with the critical operations. The expansion to greater risks of transactions is followed by gradual expansion, but it does not disrupt the system. The APIs and data formats of both legacy banking systems and digital wallets are complicated to integrate, and a lot of attention should be paid to the coordination. Speed and reliability of real-time streaming have to be put in place to prevent lagging alerts. Through pilot testing, suggestions are also made on how to make the thresholds better, the priority of alerts, and the general workflow that will make the system viable to be deployed on a large scale.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Operational aspects have to be considered to provide a system performance during different conditions (Hasan et al., 2022). New modules and legacy systems have to be synchronized to avoid duplication of processing or loss of data. Processing large volumes of transactions demands sufficient computing power, load balancing, and data piping. Failover servers and backups are also a part of redundancy mechanisms that ensure that even financial systems are available in the event of unanticipated outages. The bottlenecks or failures can be noted early by doing consistent monitoring of the operations of the system (Saleh et al., 2023). Workflow design in organizations should ensure that they have the ability to deliver performance without affecting the speed and accuracy of their transactions and without having to compromise efficiency or reliability for all types of users and transactions.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
The system must also be stable, and this must be assessed and reviewed at all times (Xu et al., 2023). The detection latency, the accuracy, and the false-positive rates are the performance metrics that provide an understanding of whether the system is working or not. The model will be kept abreast with changing behaviour by setting parameters (periodically) that are subject to parameter change as per the observed trends in transactions. Administrators could be notified about potential system errors by using automated monitoring tools, and patterns and anomalies could be visualised in dashboards (Cobbe et al., 2021). The mechanisms support the decision maker process and allow an intervention of the organisation in good time at the expense of reducing the likelihood of fraud that would otherwise remain unnoticed. Monitoring also provides a source of continuous improvement, such that the system remains responsive to changes in operations and the environment.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
6.2 User-Centred Design and Alert Systems. }
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
The effective alerts should be designed to ensure that users and internal teams can respond to suspicious transactions (Plathottam et al., 2023). The alerts should give a clear statement of the nature of the flagged activity, and provide directions on what should be done. An insufficiently formulated alert can bewilder or lead to alert fatigue, leading to a reduction of the possibility of a timely response. There is a need to balance between details and clarity alerts should also give adequate information to arrive at a decision, but they should not offer too many technicalities to users (Murmann and Karegar, 2021). Periodic re-scanning of the content of the alerts: This assists the end-users and analysts in understanding the relevance of the transactions flagged so that they can be intelligent and responsive to the anomalies.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
An anthropocentric approach to the development of alerts takes into account different degrees of digital literacy among the user population (Khan et al., 2021). The notifications should be available on mobile devices and should include guidance within the app to explain what should be done. The use of simple language, icons, and step-by-step instructions is also used to make the user comprehend the situation and act accordingly. Feedback systems enable users to report false positives or ambiguous notifications and are helpful to keep the system under continuous improvement. During the process of user testing and refining the alert design, it is possible to make sure that the system will be comprehensible and practical to all users without losing interest and trust in the monitoring opportunities of the platform.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
According to Adekunle et al (2023), Internal dashboard: dashboards are of central importance in monitoring flagged transactions. Dashboards should visually present data in a format that is easy to perform actions on, and analysts are able to prioritize alerts effectively. Drill-down is used to investigate the anomalies further, giving the background information like the history of transactions, patterns of user behavior, and device details. The alerts should be prioritized so that the operational load is minimized and cases that have high priority are addressed right away (Adekunle et al., 2023). Quick evaluation of flagged activity is provided by visual indicators, overview statistics, and automated sorting tools. Recurring improvement of dashboard dependencies through user feedback and monitoring statistics can be beneficial to ensure that operational efficacy and user-friendliness balance are maintained in the dashboard.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
6.3 Scalability and Maintenance.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Scalability is a requirement to make sure that the detection system will be able to support the rising transaction levels and the number of users (Khan et al., 2021). Since fintech platforms will grow, computational resources must be well-designed to ensure responsiveness and reduce delays. Whether to deploy on-premises or cloud-based influences the flexibility, maintenance, and system resilience (Murmann & Karegar, 2021). The allocation of resources efficiently, load balancing, and optimization of the network are essential to the support of performance. Scalability planning is another operation whereby the peak of transactions is to be considered, as well as maintaining the same level of monitoring without service degradation. Scaling of the system will ensure that it is reliable in monitoring the transaction and avoiding bottleneck operations with increased usage.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
To keep the detection effective, model retraining and lifelong learning are required regularly (Khan et al., 2021). The trends of frauds are dynamic, and the inclusion of new transactional data makes the system relevant. Planned retraining cycles enable models to cope with the change of user behavior without varying detection thresholds. Validation metrics should also be monitored with a view to determining the accuracy, false positives, and false negatives over time. Integration of different sources of data increases coverage and sensitivity of the model. These updates are useful in enabling the system to react dynamically to the new threats whilst still ensuring that the old patterns do not affect the detection reliability of the system, so that it can continue to operate effectively, as displayed by the wide range of users.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Operational oversight is used to make sure that automated decisions are understandable, auditable, and trustworthy (Cobbe et al., 2021). Staff should look through flagged transactions, confirm the accuracy of the transaction, and validate odd patterns. Having human-in-the-loop control helps avoid excess dependence on automated detection, so every decision would be made in line with organizational policies and compliance regulations. The accountability and regulatory alignment are supported by audit logs and clear decision paths. Constant monitoring of performance can enable working teams to vary workflows and thresholds that are determined by observed trends. According to Kass et al. (2025), the system also ensures that, with human supervision and automated detection, it is adaptive and accountable and delivers dependable mitigation of the fraud without undermining the integrity of the institution with regard to its governance or compliance strategies.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\qc\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10\ab \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\b\f5\loch
7.0 Conclusion}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Isolation Forest-based detection systems have demonstrated a high potential in improving fraud prevention in mobile money and digital wallet systems. Transactions can be monitored in real time, which enables the detection of anomalies in a short period, minimizing financial risk and operational interference. The scalable architecture of the system can sustain expansion in the transaction volumes and number of users, and modular integration also ensures that the existing platforms are compatible with the system. In comparison, it has been identified that Isolation Forest is a reliable solution to various transaction patterns and can be adopted in the U.S. financial ecosystem.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Future studies should examine hybrid models that combine Isolation Forest with supervised approaches, statistical methods, and rule-based systems to enhance detection accuracy. Real-time streaming implementation presents challenges in latency, throughput, and model update mechanisms that require further investigation. Cross-platform and multi-source data integration, including device-level data, geolocation, and behavioral biometrics, will enhance anomaly detection coverage. Explainable AI techniques specifically designed for Isolation Forest could address interpretability limitations, enabling better understanding of why transactions are flagged. Longitudinal studies on model drift and performance degradation over time are needed to inform retraining schedules and threshold adjustment strategies. Regulatory compliance frameworks for unsupervised detection systems require development to ensure transparency and auditability. User-centered design research for alert systems, particularly for underbanked populations with varying digital literacy levels, will improve adoption and trust. Cross-country validation studies can determine the transferability of strategies across different regulatory environments and user behavior patterns. The analysis will assist in ensuring system responsiveness through iterative testing, model retraining, and optimization of alert workflows to minimize disruption to legitimate users while maintaining effective fraud detection.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af8\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af4\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa160\ltrpar\hyphpar0\cf0\f4\fs24\lang1033\kerning1\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sl480\slmult1\fi720\sb0\sa0{\rtlch\af10 \ltrch\hich\af5\loch\f5\loch
Such systems should be adopted more widely to contribute to financial inclusion by safeguarding the populations that are underbanked, improving consumer confidence, and being compliant with regulatory provisions. The deployment in the long term promotes innovation in digital finance and builds resilient and adaptable ecosystems that protect users, enhance operational efficiency, and add to the overall financial well-being.}
